'''Tomi Shrine''' (とみじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Sakurai|Q127026|WD=Q127026|1=Sakurai, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} (small), and its former rank was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}. It is identified with the '''Tomi Shrine''' of Shikinokami District, {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}}, listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. Until the {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} period it was called '''Notomiya'''.

=== History ===
The date of foundation is unknown, but according to shrine tradition this shrine was originally located on {{ill|lt=Torimiyama|Q18700112|WD=Q18700112|1=Mount Torimi}}. Torimiyama is said to be the sacred ritual ground (matsuriniwa) where {{ill|lt=Emperor Jinmu|Q200188|WD=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}}, Japan's first {{ill|lt=emperor|Q208233|WD=Q208233|1=Emperor of Japan}}, worshipped the imperial ancestral deities and heavenly deities in spring, second month, of his fourth regnal year after enthronement<ref>''{{ill|lt=Nihon Shoki|Q813935|WD=Q813935|1=Nihon Shoki}}'', volume 3.</ref>. The Nihon Shoki account that he first worshipped the imperial ancestral deities after enthronement is also considered the origin and first stage of the {{ill|lt=Daijōsai#History|Q11433653|WD=Q11433653|lt=Daijōe|1=Daijosai}}.

The deity of Kamitsuo-sha, which corresponds to the main shrine, is given as {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|Q455602|WD=Q455602|lt=Ōhirume-no-Muchi-no-Mikoto|1=Amaterasu}}, though there is also a theory that it is {{ill|lt=Nigihayahi|Q10949054|WD=Q10949054|lt=Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto|1=Nigihayahi}}.

In the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}} it was listed as a shikinaisha, but in {{ill|lt=Ten'ei|Q1193915|WD=Q1193915|1=Ten'ei}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1112|Q19525|WD=Q19525|1=1112}}), a landslide caused the shrine buildings to be moved to the present location.

In {{ill|lt=1940|Q18633|WD=Q18633|1=1940}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 15), it was promoted from village shrine to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}.

In the 1950s, {{ill|lt=Sakurai|Q127026|WD=Q127026|1=Sakurai, Nara}} {{ill|lt=Gokoku Shrine|Q1534477|WD=Q1534477|1=Gokoku Shrines}} was founded in the precincts.

There are 13 stone monuments in the precincts (Man'yō poem monuments, haiku monuments, and waka monuments).

A distinctive feature of this shrine is that its {{ill|lt=Yatagarasu|Q745463|WD=Q745463|1=Yatagarasu}} is depicted in human form.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* Principal deity - Kamitsuo-sha: {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|Q455602|WD=Q455602|lt=Ōhirume-no-Muchi-no-Mikoto|1=Amaterasu}}
